<h1 class=3D"mt-n4 mb-4 rounded green lighten-2 p-2 pl-4 z-depth-2"> Goldba=
ch's conjecture </h1>
Goldbach wrote a letter to <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Euler.=
html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">Euler</a> dated June 7, 1742 su=
ggesting (roughly) that every even integer is the sum of two integers <i>p<=
/i> and <i>q</i> where each of <i>p</i> and <i>q</i> are either one or odd =
<a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Prime.html" class=3D"glossary" ti=
tle=3D"glossary">primes</a>.&nbsp; Now we often word this as follows:
  <blockquote>
<b>Goldbach's <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Conjecture.html" cl=
ass=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">conjecture</a></b>: Every even integer=
=20
<i>n</i> greater than two is the sum of two primes.
  </blockquote>
This is easily seen to imply=20
  <blockquote>
<i>Every</i> integer=20
<i>n</i> greater than five is the sum of three primes.
  </blockquote>
There is little doubt that both results are true, as
Euler replied to Goldbach:
  <blockquote>
That every even number is a sum of two primes, I consider an entirely certa=
in theorem in spite of that I am not able to demonstrate it.
  </blockquote>
Progress has been made on this problem, but slowly--it
may be quite awhile before the work is complete.&nbsp;
For example, it has been proven that every even integer is the sum of at mo=
st six primes (Goldbach suggests two) and in 1966 Chen proved every suffici=
ently large even integer is
the sum of a prime plus a number with no more than two prime <a href=3D"htt=
ps://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Divisor.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"gloss=
ary">factors</a> (a P<sub>2</sub>).
  <p><a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Vinogradov.html" class=3D"gl=
ossary" title=3D"glossary">Vinogradov</a> in 1937 showed that every suffici=
ently large odd integer can be written as the sum of at most three primes, =
and so every sufficiently large integer is the sum of at most four primes.&=
nbsp; One result
of <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Vinogradov.html" class=3D"glos=
sary" title=3D"glossary">Vinogradov</a>'s work is that we know Goldbach's t=
heorem=20
holds for <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/AlmostAll.html" class=
=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">almost all</a> even integers. =20
  </p><p>Various <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Heuristic.html" =
class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">heuristic</a> estimates are avaliable=
 for the number of solutions there should be to 2<i>n</i> =3D <i>p</i> + <i=
>q</i> (with <i>p</i>, <i>q</i> prime).  And these of course grew in size w=
ith <i>n</i>.
  </p><p>Recently, Jean-Marc Deshouillers, Yannick Saouter, and Herman te R=
iele have verified this up to 10<sup>14</sup> with the help of a Cray C90 a=
nd various workstations.&nbsp;
If we will accept the <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/RiemannHypo=
thesis.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">Riemann Hypothesis</a>, =
then this is enough to prove the <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/=
OddGoldbachConjecture.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">odd Goldb=
ach conjecture</a>: Every <i>odd</i> integer greater than five is the sum o=
f three primes.
  </p><p>Descartes also was aware of the two prime version of Goldbach's co=
njecture before Goldbach was.&nbsp; So is it misnamed?&nbsp;  <a href=3D"ht=
tps://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Erdos.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossa=
ry">Erd=C3=B6s</a> said that it "is better that the conjecture be named aft=
er Goldbach because, mathematically speaking, Descartes was infinitely rich=
 and Goldbach was very poor."
  </p><p>When verifying the Goldbach conjecture for <i>n</i>
we quickly see that it is very easy to find many primes=20
which add to <i>n</i>.&nbsp; In 1923 Hardy and Littlewood=20
took the first major step toward the proof of the Goldbach=20
conjectures using their circle method [HL23].&nbsp; Among other things, the=
y conjectured that the number of ways of writing <i>n</i> as the sum of two=
 primes, G(<i>n</i>), is <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Asymptot=
icallyEqual.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">asymptotic to</a> t=
wice the <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/TwinPrimeConstant.html" =
class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">twin prime constant</a> times=20
<i>n</i>/(<a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/Log.html" class=3D"glos=
sary" title=3D"glossary">log</a> <i>n</i>)<sup>2</sup> times the product of=
 (<i>p</i>-1)/(<i>p</i>-2) taken over the prime <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/=
glossary/xpage/Divisor.html" class=3D"glossary" title=3D"glossary">divisors=
</a> <i>p</i> of <i>n</i>.
  </p><p>That is a lot of solutions for a large <i>n</i> so there will be a=
 solution with one of the prime quite small.&nbsp; For example, when checki=
ng all <i>n</i> up to 100,000,000,000,000, Richstein [Richstein2000] found =
the smaller prime is never larger than 5569 used in the following partition=
:
</p><blockquote>
389965026819938 =3D 5569 + 389965026814369.
</blockquote>
It was conjectured [GRL89] that the smallest prime in a=20
partition of <i>n</i> might be bounded by a constant times
(log <i>n</i>)<sup>2</sup> log log <i>n</i>.&nbsp; Richstein's work shows t=
hat the constant 1.603 (from <i>n</i>=3D6) sufficies for <i>n</i>  &lt;  4<=
sup>.</sup>10<sup>14</sup>.<p>
</p><p><b>See Also:</b>  <a href=3D"https://t5k.org/glossary/xpage/OddGoldb=
achConjecture.html" class=3D"glossary">OddGoldbachConjecture</a></p><p><b>R=
elated pages</b> (outside of this work)</p><ul><li> <a href=3D"https://t5k.=
org/notes/conjectures/">Prime conjectures</a></li><li> <a href=3D"http://ma=
th.nju.edu.cn/~zwsun/MSPT.htm">Mixed Sums of Primes and Other Terms</a> by =
Zhi-Wei Sun</li></ul><p><b>References:</b></p><blockquote><dl>
<dt>DRS98</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>J. M. Deshouillers</b>, <b>H. J. J.=
 te Riele</b> and <b>Y. Saouter</b>, <i>New experimental results concerning=
 the Goldbach conjecture</i>.&nbsp; In "Proc. 3rd Int. Symp. on Algorithmic=
 Number Theory," Lecture Notes in Computer Science Vol, 1423, 1998.&nbsp; p=
p. 204--215, <b><a href=3D"http://www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3D2000j=
:11143">MR 2000j:11143</a></b>
</dd><dt>FR89</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>Fliegel, H. F.</b> and <b>Rober=
tson, D. S.</b>, "Goldbach's comet: the numbers related to Goldbach's conje=
cture," <i>J. Recreational Math.</i>, <b>21</b>:1 (1989) 1--7.
</dd><dt>GRL89</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>A. Granville</b>, <b>H. J. J. =
te Riele</b> and <b>J. van de Lune</b>,"Checking the Goldbach conjecture on=
 a vector computer" in <i>Number theory and its applications</i>.&nbsp; R. =
A. Mollin editor, Kluwer, 1989.&nbsp; Dordrect, pp. 423--433,=20
</dd><dt>HL23</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>G. H. Hardy</b> and <b>J. E. Li=
ttlewood</b>, "Some problems of `partitio numerorum' : III: on the expressi=
on of a number as a sum of primes," <i>Acta Math.</i>, <b>44</b> (1923) 1-7=
0.&nbsp; Reprinted in "Collected Papers of G. H. Hardy," Vol. I, pp. 561-63=
0, Clarendon Press, Oxford, 1966.
</dd><dt>Ramare95</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>O. Ramar=C3=A9</b>, "On Sch=
nirelmann's constant," <i>Ann. Sc. Norm. Super. Pisa</i>, <b>22</b>:4 (1995=
) 645-706.&nbsp; <b><a href=3D"http://www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3D9=
7a:11167">MR 97a:11167</a></b>
</dd><dt>Ribenboim95</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>P. Ribenboim</b>, <i>The=
 new book of prime number records</i>, 3rd edition, Springer-Verlag, New Yo=
rk, NY, 1995.&nbsp; pp. xxiv+541, ISBN 0-387-94457-5. <b><a href=3D"http://=
www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3D96k:11112">MR 96k:11112</a></b> <span s=
tyle=3D"color: #000033;">[An excellent resource for those with some college=
 mathematics. Basically a Guinness Book of World Records for primes with mu=
ch of the relevant mathematics. The extensive bibliography is seventy-five =
pages.]</span>
</dd><dt>Richstein2000</dt><dd class=3D"BibItem"> <b>J. Richstein</b>, "Ver=
ifying the goldbach conjecture up to 4=C2=B7 10<sup>14</sup>," <i>Math. Com=
